##Interview | Ryuichi Sakamoto: humans are slightly off track, a little broken monkeys

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

Tsunamis and disease, they remind us once again that we are a part of nature.

By Kong Bingxin

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A BLOND POW walks up to him in the jungle off Java island in the South Ocean. And he revealed the truth of the trembling eyes, that section of fine broken, mysterious, sad music, has been masonry falling Cherry Snow Chaos, cloud flying cross, can not cross between the perfect without regret.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Beijing, Dalian, Changchun, people go to the sunset of the empire twilight, there are not found in the grandmother, was hidden cricket, HALF OF LIFE is not turn head empty sense of loss and relief. There was an off-key piano behind the scenes, and he spent two weeks composing and recording more than forty pieces.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
He was part of the first three-man Ymo (the highest-educated, nicknamed "professor") Band to move from Japan to the West in the late 1970s, and as a young man he combined classic, avant-garde, breakthrough and rebellious qualities.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Also is to read after the prosperity of light, gentle old, believe in "tune out of nature, all living things sound. ". Hold Plastic buckets upside down on your head and listen to the rain beat on them, blow a gentle breeze on the conch, and wander through the woods, treading on the leaves. To Africa to capture the rhythms of primitive tribal dance. Go to the North Pole, take a recording device, "fishing" in the semi-melting snow water.

Ryuichi Sakamoto. Talent, arrogance, no boundaries, and good looks give him almost everything a literary icon needs.

He came to China once in 2018. At that time, each big V of the cultural circle in the capital basically reposted the micro-blog related to him. In 2020, he was concerned about the Chinese families affected by the outbreak, and in due course offered his own song, Aqua.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It all started with the Beijing Contemporary Art Foundation and the summer sounds'2020 Love Edition of Mom and Dad's life festival. In the most difficult days since the Spring Festival, many outstanding cross-boundary artists and creators have shared the power of art with their parents and children who live in solitary homes through online / Video / live broadcast platforms.

On February 22, the Beijing Contemporary Art Foundation released a video of Ryuichi Sakamoto playing "Aqua. ". It is worth mentioning that "Aqua" is one of Sakamoto's masterpieces from his "BTTB" (Back To The Basic, "there's a piece of music on The album that reminds me of my childhood") , a decade or two ago.

He left a message encouraging Chinese children: "It must be hard not to be able to go out and play, but now that you don't have to go to school, you can do fun things at home. ". Don't just play games. Use the time to read a lot of books and listen to a lot of music. Drawing, writing poetry, playing an instrument and watching movies are also good choices. And don't forget to do a little gymnastics at home. Try to get through it."

Sakamoto Ryuichi also sent a message, know that now is a difficult time for everyone, but hope that everyone can try not to panic, grasp the situation, calmly act. Even if we have to "keep our distance" from those around us, we can still help each other. Sincerely pray that no more people will suffer. Please be safe.

On the night of February 29th, the instrument Ryuichi Sakamoto used in another online concert became a hit -- a 'made in Wuhan, China' cymbal. At the end of the song, the professor turned to the camera and said in Chinese, "come on, everybody! "

Ryuichi Sakamoto, who is nearing the age of seven, is known to the general public in China for the soundtrack of Bertolucci's film The Last Emperor. The Last Emperor won him the 60th Academy Award for Best Original Score, and he and Bertolucci teamed up again for the screening of the sky, which won best film score at the 48th Golden Globes. He also wrote and conducted music for the opening ceremony of the Barcelona Olympics, and was the musical producer of The Revenant, which won the Academy Award for Best Actor title for his painstaking efforts with a water pistol.

Of course, for many fans of "Merry Christmas, Lawrence, " the professor is a man with his own BGM, a David Bowie and a demon, and in this film, no more so than the endless musings of the notes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In addition to music and movies, Ryuichi Sakamoto has always been concerned about issues such as race, war, the environment and climate.

Passionate Youth, he was keen on left-wing theory, actively engaged in social activities. More than 40 years later, after the Fukushima nuclear disaster following the March 11 earthquake, and amid anti-nuclear demonstrations, he lamented that it had been years "since there was such a protest. ".

In 2014, Ryuichi Sakamoto was diagnosed with throat cancer. As a cancer survivor, he had a visceral sense of pain about the disease, referring to his "crying during chemotherapy. ". He admits that he is a weak man, but that does not mean he is incompetent, and that "weakness" may have triggered more empathy, including in the case of.

In fact, like his favorite Japanese historical figure, Natsume Sōseki, Ryuichi Sakamoto was complex, sensitive, and often in a middle position, between East and west, tradition and modernity, it's between the public and the private.

I wish the professor would just go on. The hair is still thick, the eyebrows are still moving, when doing music, smile is still naive.

In a recent interview with Xinmin Weekly, Ryuichi Sakamoto discussed his thoughts on the epidemic and music.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xinmin Weekly: You made a live video of piano music from New York to cheer the Chinese people during the war. Is there any particular reason why we chose "Aqua" ?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: Actually I recorded Aqua  and Energy flow this time, because Aqua  is better, so I chose it. In the midst of the epidemic, I thought these two pieces of music would calm the listener's mind.

Xinmin Weekly: The Chinese have been moved by the Japanese offer of assistance since the outbreak of the new crown pneumonia. And facing epidemic situation gradually not optimistic Japan, in the Japanese Chinese also began to take to the streets, for Japanese friends to distribute free masks. China and Japan are separated by a strip of water. How do you understand the sentiment of "throwing a peach to me in return for a plum" ? What are your expectations for the relationship between the two countries?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: the COVID-19 epidemic is a severe test for both countries, and I hope that under the circumstances of mutual help, the people can also get to know each other better and enhance their feelings. This is the Chinese saying "blessing in disguise" it.

Xinmin Weekly: What do you think are the main aspects of art's role in fighting the epidemic in the world today?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: Art and music do not have the actual production capacity, nor can they be used for food. Yet from the moment we were born on this planet, we have been engaged in art and music-related activities. I don't know what it is, but art and music are essential to human survival, and that's a fact.

Xinmin Weekly: This time, your music is playing not only for parents, but also for children. How does art close the modern distance and promote the communication of love?

Sakamoto Ryuichi: Maybe because music is from 0-year-old infants to the elderly, can clap hands together, shake the body together, to enjoy it. Even if we don't speak the same language, we can enjoy the music together.

Xinmin Weekly: What advice and blessings would you like to send to the people who have been affected by the outbreak?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: Please listen to the advice of professionals on how to prevent and respond to the virus, and I will do the same.

A few years ago, I was seriously ill and suddenly had a lot of free time after decades, during which I listened to a lot of composers I had never heard before. There's been a lot of new discoveries, and there's a lot more music to like.

I think everyone in the daily busy study and work, there should be a lot of want to do but do not do it, use this time to try in-depth it?

Xinmin Weekly: Human beings are so vulnerable to unknown viruses and deep rooted obsessions. This outbreak caught us off guard, and in 2014, you were diagnosed with throat cancer. How do you feel about life and death now?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: I spend a lot of time on my daily tasks and chores, and I rarely think about long-term, profound issues like life and death, but when diseases and unusual situations like this happen suddenly, i think everyone has to think about these things. In fact, I'm grateful for this cancer thing, because it made me realize once again the important thing that is often forgotten: that my life, and my body, are subordinate to nature.

Xinmin Weekly: you studied classical music, but you became a promoter and innovator of modern Japanese music, with a variety of styles. In fact, when you were young, you were also a left wing hothead, reading Mao Zedong and listening to the left wing Marxists, pitchdale pedestrians. Does left-wing thinking directly influence your music?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: I don't think there was a direct impact. When I was young, I thought about whether my music should be political or not. I thought about what is political music. But then my thinking changed. Although music was influenced by politics, economics or the media of the time, making music itself was supported by music theory, grammar and emotion, there is no need to be unduly influenced by external factors such as politics or economics.

Xinmin Weekly: Writing Music, acting in movies, it seems like you can do anything. So you were arrogant then, but in an interview with the media, you admitted that you wouldn't be friends with yourself now. You think the rebellion wasn't deep enough? Now, is it settling enough?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: Yes, I think I was a very selfish and arrogant guy when I was young. If I met my younger self today, I'd think the guy was too self-righteous to be his friend.

Xinmin Weekly: In China, you are best known for the soundtrack to the film The Last Emperor. At the same time, one of your most classic songs, "Merry Christmas Mr. Lawrence, " also let the young literati in China never tire of hearing it. This song "Merry Christmas Lawrence" , will you play "aesthetic fatigue" and "unbearable" ? Do you have a favorite album or song in your writing career?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: especially after the production of the theme song "Merry Christmas Laurence" , because it was the only thing people wanted to hear, and I wasn't happy to play it again, I didn't play it again for about 10 years.

I write music like my own children, there will be no separation, there is no favorite song.

Xinmin Weekly: In 2011, after the Fukushima nuclear disaster, you and your friends found a piano that had been submerged by the tsunami. The Piano was badly out of tune, but you played it anyway, there's even some harsh music. Now, you are more in pursuit of a "natural sound" , more reject the artificial calibration, why? Do you think the contradiction between natural ecology and human civilization is difficult to reconcile?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: It seems to me that humans are monkeys that are a little off their natural course. Instead of living according to the laws of nature, he was always trying to contrive his own unique environment. As is the case with civilization, so is money and music, neither of which is a product of nature.

And the tsunami and the disease, both remind us once again that we are part of nature.

Xinmin Weekly: Do you think people stop thinking seriously, stop caring about weighty topics?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: There is a tendency all over the world that the speed and pace of the economy is dominating life. I think people should try to slow down.

It takes time to make music and to think about philosophy. The same is true of raising forests and children.

Xinmin Weekly: Last year, the Documentary Sakamoto Ryuichi: the Finale, released in Chinese theaters, chronicled your life from 2012 to 2017. So, what have you been up to for the last two years? What are your new plans for the next phase?

Ryuichi Sakamoto: There are so many projects going on at the same time, you can't say them all at once. I've been a little busy lately, and I need to slow down and try to focus on one thing for as long as possible.
